issue_details.brief_description:
I am submitting this issue regarding the City and Borough of Juneau’s (CBJ) proposal to increase the seasonal passenger head tax specifically on independent, small-group shore excursions beginning with the 2026 cruise season. While the intent of the proposal is to address community impacts from high visitor volumes and to help fund harbor and downtown infrastructure, the structure of the proposed increase disproportionately affects small and medium-sized local tour operators that rely heavily on cruise passengers but do not have the pricing power or margins of the large cruise lines and national chains.

Under the draft ordinance currently being discussed at the local level, an additional $7 per cruise passenger would be assessed on any guided shore excursion operated by a business with under $3 million in annual gross revenue, on top of existing per-passenger and port fees already in place. Larger operators (over $3 million in revenue) would see a smaller per-passenger increase due to a tiered credit based on volume agreements with the cruise lines. As a Juneau-based, locally owned operator that runs small-group whale watching, hiking, and cultural experiences, we estimate this would increase our effective per-guest cost by approximately 12–15% on some tours.

For context, our business, Northern Lights Adventure Tours, LLC, employs 14–18 seasonal staff each summer, the majority of whom are local residents or students from the University of Alaska Southeast. Roughly 80% of our bookings are from cruise visitors, though we contract directly with guests or small travel agencies rather than signing exclusive agreements with the major cruise lines. Our typical tour price point is already higher than mass-market excursions because we focus on small groups (maximum 10–12 guests), interpretation, and low-impact practices.

We are deeply concerned that the proposed increase, as written, will:
1) Force small operators to substantially raise prices or cut wages/staff to absorb the fee;
2) Reduce the diversity of shore excursion options available to visitors, undermining the visitor experience ATIA and the state work hard to promote;
3) Potentially push some local operators out of business or force them to sell to larger companies that can negotiate better terms with the cruise lines;
4) Create confusion for visitors who may not understand why their independent tour is suddenly significantly more expensive than a comparable product sold onboard.

We fully recognize and share the community’s concerns about congestion, infrastructure wear and tear, and the need for sustainable tourism management. We are not opposed to contributing fairly to solutions. However, we believe that the current structure of the proposed tax increase is misaligned with ATIA’s broader goals of supporting locally owned businesses, dispersing visitor spending, and incentivizing high-quality, small-group experiences that are generally more sustainable and better received by both visitors and residents.

We are asking ATIA to review this developing issue, engage with CBJ and local stakeholders, and consider adopting a position that supports a more equitable and impact-based funding approach—for example, a structure that is neutral across company size or that is more directly tied to actual infrastructure usage rather than gross revenue thresholds that inadvertently penalize smaller operators.

